			<h2>What is Recurrent Pregnancy Loss?</h2>

			<div class="definition-box">
				<h3>ASRM Definition</h3>
				<p>Recurrent pregnancy loss (RPL) is defined as <strong>two or more</strong> pregnancy losses before 20 weeks gestation. It affects <strong>2-4% of couples</strong> trying to conceive.</p>
			</div>

			<div class="stats-grid stats-grid-3">
				<div class="stat-card">
					<div class="stat-number">2-4%</div>
					<div class="stat-label">Experience 2+ losses</div>
				</div>
				<div class="stat-card">
					<div class="stat-number">0.5-1%</div>
					<div class="stat-label">Experience 3+ losses</div>
				</div>
				<div class="stat-card highlight">
					<div class="stat-number">60-75%</div>
					<div class="stat-label">Success in next pregnancy</div>
					<div class="stat-detail">(with unexplained RPL)</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="callout callout-warning">
				<span class="callout-icon">‚è±Ô∏è</span>
				<div class="callout-content">
					<strong>When to seek evaluation:</strong> ASRM recommends a full RPL workup after 2 consecutive losses, especially if you're over 35. Don't wait for a third loss to get answers.
				</div>
			</div>

			<p class="citation">Sources: <a href="https://www.asrm.org/practice-guidance/practice-committee-documents/evaluation-and-treatment-of-recurrent-pregnancy-loss-a-committee-opinion-2012/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASRM Committee Opinion</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554460/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NCBI StatPearls - RPL</a></p>

			<h2>Causes of Recurrent Loss</h2>

			<p>When miscarriage tissue is tested along with standard RPL workup, a cause can be identified in <strong>over 90%</strong> of cases. The most common cause is chromosomal abnormality in the embryo.</p>

