			<h2>RPL Testing Workup</h2>

			<h3>Standard Testing (Recommended)</h3>

			<div class="testing-grid">
				<div class="testing-card">
					<div class="testing-header">
						<span class="testing-icon">üß¨</span>
						<h4>Genetic Testing</h4>
					</div>
					<ul>
						<li><strong>Karyotype (both partners):</strong> Blood test for balanced translocations or chromosomal rearrangements</li>
						<li><strong>POC testing:</strong> Genetic analysis of miscarriage tissue</li>
					</ul>
					<div class="testing-cost">
						<span class="cost-label">Typical Cost:</span>
						<span class="cost-amount">$200-$500 per karyotype; $500-$1,500 for POC</span>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="testing-card">
					<div class="testing-header">
						<span class="testing-icon">üîç</span>
						<h4>Uterine Evaluation</h4>
					</div>
					<ul>
						<li><strong>Transvaginal ultrasound:</strong> Basic uterine assessment</li>
						<li><strong>Saline sonogram (SIS):</strong> Enhanced cavity visualization</li>
						<li><strong>Hysteroscopy:</strong> Direct visualization and treatment</li>
						<li><strong>MRI:</strong> If anomaly suspected</li>
					</ul>
					<div class="testing-cost">
						<span class="cost-label">Typical Cost:</span>
						<span class="cost-amount">$300-$1,000 imaging; $2,000-$10,000 hysteroscopy</span>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="testing-card">
					<div class="testing-header">
						<span class="testing-icon">ü©∏</span>
						<h4>Blood Clotting Panel</h4>
					</div>
					<ul>
						<li><strong>Antiphospholipid antibodies:</strong> Lupus anticoagulant, anticardiolipin, beta-2 glycoprotein</li>
						<li><strong>Factor V Leiden</strong></li>
						<li><strong>Prothrombin gene mutation</strong></li>
						<li><strong>Protein C, S, Antithrombin III</strong></li>
					</ul>
					<div class="testing-cost">
						<span class="cost-label">Typical Cost:</span>
						<span class="cost-amount">$500-$2,000</span>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="testing-card">
					<div class="testing-header">
						<span class="testing-icon">‚öóÔ∏è</span>
						<h4>Hormonal Testing</h4>
					</div>
					<ul>
						<li><strong>TSH and thyroid antibodies</strong></li>
						<li><strong>Prolactin</strong></li>
						<li><strong>Hemoglobin A1C</strong> (diabetes screening)</li>
						<li><strong>Day 3 FSH, estradiol, AMH</strong></li>
						<li><strong>Progesterone</strong> (mid-luteal phase)</li>
					</ul>
					<div class="testing-cost">
						<span class="cost-label">Typical Cost:</span>
						<span class="cost-amount">$200-$800</span>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h3>Additional Testing (Case-by-Case)</h3>

			<div class="additional-tests">
				<div class="test-item">
					<strong>Endometrial biopsy</strong>
					<span>Check for chronic endometritis (infection)</span>
				</div>
				<div class="test-item">
					<strong>Sperm DNA fragmentation</strong>
					<span>If male factor suspected</span>
				</div>
				<div class="test-item">
					<strong>ERA (Endometrial Receptivity Analysis)</strong>
					<span>Timing of implantation window</span>
				</div>
				<div class="test-item">
					<strong>Immunological panels</strong>
					<span>NK cells, cytokines (controversial)</span>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="callout callout-warning">
				<span class="callout-icon">‚ö†Ô∏è</span>
				<div class="callout-content">
					<strong>Note on immune testing:</strong> Testing for natural killer cells, cytokines, and other immune factors is controversial. Many reproductive immunology treatments lack strong evidence. Discuss thoroughly with your doctor before pursuing expensive immune protocols.
				</div>
			</div>

			<h2>Treatment Options</h2>

			<h3>Treatments for Identified Causes</h3>

			<div class="treatment-cards">
				<div class="treatment-card">
					<div class="treatment-header aps">
						<h4>Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)</h4>
						<span class="success-badge">70-80% success</span>
					</div>
					<div class="treatment-body">
						<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Low-dose aspirin (81mg daily) + heparin or Lovenox injections throughout pregnancy</p>
						<p class="contrast-note">Without treatment: 10-20% live birth rate</p>
						<div class="treatment-cost">$100-$500/month</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="treatment-card">
					<div class="treatment-header uterine">
						<h4>Uterine Abnormalities</h4>
						<span class="success-badge">Varies by condition</span>
					</div>
					<div class="treatment-body">
						<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Surgical correction via hysteroscopy</p>
						<ul>
							<li>Septum resection</li>
							<li>Fibroid removal (myomectomy)</li>
							<li>Adhesion removal (for Asherman's)</li>
						</ul>
						<div class="treatment-cost">$5,000-$15,000</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="treatment-card">
					<div class="treatment-header genetic">
						<h4>Parental Chromosomal Translocation</h4>
						<span class="success-badge">Significantly reduces risk</span>
					</div>
					<div class="treatment-body">
						<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> IVF with PGT-SR (preimplantation genetic testing for structural rearrangements)</p>
						<p>Tests embryos before transfer to select those with normal chromosomes.</p>
						<div class="treatment-cost">$20,000-$35,000/cycle</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="treatment-card">
					<div class="treatment-header thyroid">
						<h4>Thyroid Dysfunction</h4>
						<span class="success-badge">Goal: TSH &lt;2.5</span>
					</div>
					<div class="treatment-body">
						<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Thyroid medication (levothyroxine) to normalize TSH levels during pregnancy</p>
						<div class="treatment-cost">$10-$50/month</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h3>Empiric Treatments (When Cause Unknown)</h3>

			<div class="empiric-grid">
				<div class="empiric-card">
					<h4>Progesterone Supplementation</h4>
					<p>Vaginal or intramuscular progesterone starting after ovulation or positive test.</p>
					<div class="evidence-note">
						<strong>Evidence:</strong> PRISM trial showed benefit for women with bleeding in early pregnancy and history of loss
					</div>
					<div class="empiric-cost">$50-$300/month</div>
				</div>

				<div class="empiric-card">
					<h4>Baby Aspirin (81mg)</h4>
					<p>Often prescribed empirically even without diagnosed APS.</p>
					<div class="evidence-note">
						<strong>Evidence:</strong> Low risk, may have modest benefit
					</div>
					<div class="empiric-cost">~$10/month</div>
				</div>

				<div class="empiric-card">
					<h4>IVF with PGT-A</h4>
					<p>Testing embryos for chromosomal abnormalities before transfer.</p>
					<div class="evidence-note">
						<strong>Evidence:</strong> Can reduce miscarriage rate per transfer, especially for women over 35
					</div>
					<div class="empiric-cost">$20,000-$30,000</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h2>When to Consider Other Options</h2>

			<div class="options-grid">
				<div class="option-card">
					<h3>ü•ö Donor Eggs</h3>
					<p>Consider if:</p>
					<ul>
						<li>Multiple losses with chromosomally abnormal embryos</li>
						<li>Advanced maternal age (40+) with RPL</li>
						<li>PGT-A shows most/all embryos are abnormal</li>
						<li>Diminished ovarian reserve</li>
					</ul>
					<a href="/treatments/third-party/" class="option-link">Learn about donor options ‚Üí</a>
				</div>

				<div class="option-card">
